document.caption: Magpie — melodious carolling — A beautiful songbird, the Australian magpie makes a wide variety of chortling and carolling calls, many of which are complex and vary by location. They can be heard across most of Australia, wherever there is a combination of trees and adjacent open areas. Magpies (Gymnorhina tibicenhas) are territorial and live in small to large family groups.

document.caption: Kookaburra — ‘koo-koo-koo-koo-koo-kaa-kaa-kaa' — The loud, cackling laugh of the aptly named laughing kookaburra is actually a territorial call, made by pairs or family groups to define their patch. The famous call can be heard throughout QLD, NSW, VIC and SA (where they're endemic) and in TAS and south-west WA (where they're introduced). The laughing kookaburra (Dacelo novaeguineae) is a type of kingfisher.

document.caption: Butcherbird — melodic and maniacal — The grey butcherbird's lively call is made up of a melodious song punctuated with noisy, slightly maniacal cackling, often performed as a duet. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Let's quickly dip back to the US for a moment and look at some other interesting news about their housing market. This week the US's popular 30-year fixed mortgage rate hit the highest level since April 2002, with the average shooting up to 7.09%, according to mortgage finance agency Freddie Mac. That's up from 6.96% last week, and is nearly a full 2 percentage point higher than where it was this time last year. The average 15-year rate also surged to 6.46%, up from 6.34% the previous week — and is also the highest level since April 2002. The jump in mortgage rates comes as the yield on the 10-year Treasury note yield, which acts as a benchmark for mortgage rates, hit their highest level in 10 months — supported by concerns that strong domestic demand in the US could give the Federal Reserve a reason to lift rates again. "The last time the 30-year fixed-rate mortgage exceeded seven percent was last November, " said Freddie Mac's chief economist Sam Khater. "Demand has been impacted by affordability headwinds, but low inventory remains the root cause of stalling home sales."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: US 30-year fixed mortgage rate jumps to a 21-year high

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: China's flagging economy is under pressure, and the Western world is feeling the pain. Australia's biggest trading partner has posted a string of big data misses as it grapples with a property crisis and an economy-wide slowdown. On Tuesday policymakers announced a cut to key interest rates, but markets remain deeply pessimistic about Beijing pulling the trigger on major stimulus measures. So can the Chinese economy get out of its rut? The Business host Alicia Barry spoke to Michael Every, the global strategist for Rabobank earlier this week for his take. You can watch their full chat below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ICYMI: Here's why China has spooked global markets
